</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF966A29F82A928B16FABE5B" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" type="distribution">
<caption id="90EB6676FF966A29F82A928B16FABE5B" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6398302" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6398302" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6398302/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" targetBox="[1391,1982,1085,1498]" targetPageId="109">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF966A29F82A928B16FABE5B" blockId="109.[2005,2599,1080,1503]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF966A29F82A928B1686BFC1" bold="true" box="[2006,2182,1234,1267]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Distribution.</emphasis>
Extreme E 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF966A29F6D1928B17CBBFC1" box="[2349,2507,1234,1267]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
and C Asian mountains E through 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF966A29F69F92A317E9BE29" box="[2403,2537,1274,1307]" name="Mongolia" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
and NE 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF966A29F7F393731663BE71" box="[2063,2147,1322,1347]" name="China" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">China</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF966A29F76A937316EABE71" box="[2198,2282,1322,1347]" name="South Korea" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Korea</collectingCountry>
and Russian Far East, including Sakhalin I.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF966A29F82993291697BCA2" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" type="description">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF966A29F82993291697BCA2" blockId="109.[2005,2599,1080,1503]" lastBlockId="109.[1387,2598,1510,2451]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF966A29F829932916CCBEA3" bold="true" box="[2005,2252,1392,1425]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F67593291420BEA3" box="[2441,2592,1392,1425]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="mm" value="49.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="48.0">48-50 mm</quantity>
, tail 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F7EC93C516AABE8B" box="[2064,2218,1436,1465]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="4.6" metricValueMin="4.4" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="mm" value="45.0" valueMax="46.0" valueMin="44.0">44-46 mm</quantity>
, ear 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F70193C51797BE8B" box="[2301,2455,1436,1465]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" metricValueMax="3.3" metricValueMin="3.1" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="mm" value="32.0" valueMax="33.0" valueMin="31.0">31-33 mm</quantity>
, hindfoot c. 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F817939B163FBEED" box="[2027,2111,1474,1503]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
, forearm 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F736939B175DBEED" box="[2250,2397,1474,1503]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" metricValueMax="4.2" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="mm" value="41.0" valueMax="42.0" valueMin="40.0">40-42 mm</quantity>
; weight 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F628939B141FBEED" box="[2516,2591,1474,1503]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="g" value="8.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="7.0">7-9 g</quantity>
. Similar to the Brown Long-eared Bat (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF966A29F88293BF19F7BD35" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1918,2039,1510,1543]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Plecotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="auritus">P. auritus</taxonomicName>
) but forearm is slightly larger, whereas it is shorter than in the Japanese Long-eared Bat (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF966A29F7F2905416BBBD1C" authorityName="G. M. Allen" authorityYear="1908" box="[2062,2235,1549,1582]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Plecotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sacrimontis">P. sacrimontis</taxonomicName>
) and Kozlov’s Long-eared Bat (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF966A29FA48906D182DBD67" authorityName="Bobrinskii" authorityYear="1926" box="[1460,1581,1588,1621]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Plecotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kozlovi">P kozlovi</taxonomicName>
). Fur almost woolly, dark brown dorsally and pale brown to white ventrally (hairs bicolored, with dark bases and white tips); some individuals have some pale hairs surrounding neck and throat. Toes are brown and generally covered by long dense hair. Face quite dark, naked from nose to muzzle and eyes. Membranes usually translucent and delicate. Tragus 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F96C908B191EBDC1" box="[1680,1822,1746,1779]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="mm" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13-15 mm</quantity>
long. Tibia 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF966A29F835908B1658BDC1" box="[1993,2136,1746,1779]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" unit="mm" value="19.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="18.0">18-20 mm</quantity>
long. Thumbs and claws remarkably long. Skull medium-sized, smaller in males than in females, very similar in structure to Strelkov’s Long-eared Bat (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF966A29F8F791781995BC70" authorityName="Spitzenberger" authorityYear="2006" box="[1803,1941,1825,1858]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Plecotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="strelkovi">P. strelkovi</taxonomicName>
); there is a diagnostic pronounced concavity in dorsal profile of anterior part of skull. Dental formula is 12/3, C1/1,P 2/3, M 3/3 (x2) = 36. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 32 and FNa = 50.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF966A29FA9291CE187FB337" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF966A29FA9291CE187FB337" blockId="109.[1387,2598,1510,2451]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF966A29FA9291CE1BDEBC8A" bold="true" box="[1390,1502,1943,1976]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Habitat.</emphasis>
Typical foraging habitat includes forest-steppe,taiga, and mountain and temperate mixed deciduous forest, always in highlands; also river catchment areas and riparian vegetation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF966A29FA929E4B19E1B367" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF966A29FA929E4B19E1B367" blockId="109.[1387,2598,1510,2451]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF966A29FA929E4B1871B31D" bold="true" box="[1390,1649,2066,2095]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Diet is mostly moths (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF966A29F8559E4B1659B31D" box="[1961,2137,2066,2095]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
) and mosquitoes (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF966A29F69E9E4B17D3B31D" box="[2402,2515,2066,2095]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
). Forages both by aerial-hawking and by gleaning.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF966A29FA919E0417FCB397" pageId="109" pageNumber="867" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF966A29FA919E0417FCB397" blockId="109.[1387,2598,1510,2451]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF966A29FA919E041BF4B34C" bold="true" box="[1389,1524,2141,2174]" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Breeding.</emphasis>
Breeds in small colonies of a maximum of few tens of individuals, roosting in crevices of old trees. A maternity colony was found in a cave near 
<collectingRegion id="0650F81CFF966A29F6D19EDD1791B397" box="[2349,2449,2180,2213]" country="China" name="Beijing" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">Beijing</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF966A29F65E9EDD17F8B397" box="[2466,2552,2180,2213]" name="China" pageId="109" pageNumber="867">China</collectingCountry>
